cerned that the code source for test classes might be null at runtime. It seems like dynamic class loading from Ant jar files is unsupported in native images, and the existing `ChainReaderHelperTest` may not have appropriate path entries, which makes me think that loading from jars could lead to problems. I need to avoid this approach altogether in native development.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining classloader strategies**\\n\\nI'm contemplating the child classloader solution; it seems bad unless I can catch unsupported features in the native environment. The active class only includes `Class.forName`, which can be managed with the app class. The remaining `Class$` may not be critical, but I’m considering that the user wants it.\\n\\nIt could work to catch `UnsupportedFeatureError` if necessary, but I need to ensure that tests still run under JVM. Importing `org.graalvm.internal.tck.NativeImageSupport` might be essential, but I’m unsure if this approach is allowed. It seems I should aim to avoid using it if possible.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Refining native test implementation**\\n\\nI'm analyzing the need to add a catch for the second test. It seems important to handle `UnsupportedFeatureError` on `helper.getAssembledReader` and assert with `NativeImageSupport`. However, I'm noticing that source references in native could lead to a null code source, which may cause a NullPointerException (NPE) instead. In this case, I might not be able to catch the error, so it could be better to skip the child test. Still, I want to ensure class$ coverage, so I’m considering implementing the second test in a way that checks for `UnsupportedFeatureError` specifically when running natively.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_orqasP8p4UVwWjPGy0XeYYE1|fc_07d300c03fefa7ac0169fbf93491a08194bb17c6c887537144", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/ant/ant/1.6/7a3c2521ae0c6f